---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---
<Layout title="Causal Mechanics" description="Retrieval–Induction co-gating, the 96.5% recovery result, and the perplexity illusion.">
<div class="page-top">
  <p class="eyebrow">03 — Causal Mechanics</p>
  <h1>Ablate one class.<br/>Ablate both.<br/>The difference is everything.</h1>
  <p class="lead">
    Retrieval heads find the relevant past. Induction heads copy it forward.
    Neither works without the other. This is not a correlation — it is a causal circuit.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="section">

  <h2 class="reveal">The Retrieval–Induction Co-Gate</h2>
  <p class="reveal">
    Recovery rate is the fraction of correct answers retained after ablation, relative to the
    unablated baseline.
  </p>

  <div class="ablation-grid reveal">
    <div class="ablation-card ablation-fail">
      <div class="ablation-num">0%</div>
      <div class="ablation-label">Retrieval ablated only</div>
      <p>The model cannot find what to copy. Retrieval signal is absent.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="ablation-card ablation-fail">
      <div class="ablation-num">0%</div>
      <div class="ablation-label">Induction ablated only</div>
      <p>The signal is found but never delivered. The circuit is broken mid-way.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="ablation-card ablation-win">
      <div class="ablation-num">96.5%</div>
      <div class="ablation-label">Both ablated together</div>
      <p>The circuit is cleanly removed. The residual stream is never contaminated.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout reveal">
    <strong>The Induction Dependency.</strong> Retrieval is a circuit, not an isolated head.
    Retrieval heads require Induction heads to physically copy retrieved strings into the residual
    stream. Ablating Induction destroys semantic recall completely — even when Retrieval is intact.
    This is a functional dependency, not a statistical correlation.
  </div>

  <hr/>

  <h2 class="reveal">The Perplexity Illusion</h2>
  <p class="reveal">
    Standard model evaluation uses perplexity as a proxy for capability. Our ablation experiments
    reveal a critical failure of this proxy: models can maintain near-perfect perplexity after
    Retrieval head ablation — while losing all ability to answer questions requiring long-range recall.
  </p>

  <div class="illusion-row reveal">
    <div class="illusion-col ok">
      <div class="illusion-verdict">✓ PPL preserved</div>
      <p>Perplexity on standard benchmarks drops by &lt;0.1 nats after ablating all Retrieval heads</p>
    </div>
    <div class="illusion-col fail">
      <div class="illusion-verdict">✗ Recall fails</div>
      <p>The model cannot find a name mentioned 2,000 tokens ago — even when perplexity looks fine</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout warn reveal">
    Any sparse attention system evaluated only on perplexity may appear to work while silently
    breaking long-range retrieval. HeadGenome's functional taxonomy lets you identify which heads
    are responsible for which capabilities — before you deploy.
  </div>

  <hr/>

  <h2 class="reveal">Lexical Anatomy</h2>
  <p class="reveal">
    Auditing the top attended vocabulary items for each head type on WikiText-103 confirms the
    entropy-collapse classification at the token level. Sink heads accumulate mass on punctuation
    and BOS. Induction heads show the highest top-1 token dominance.
  </p>
  <figure class="figure reveal">
    <img src={`${base}/figures/fig7_lexical.png`} alt="Lexical anatomy" loading="lazy" />
    <figcaption>Top attended tokens by head type. Sink heads are semantically inert; Induction heads are maximally focused.</figcaption>
  </figure>

</div>
</Layout>

<style>
.section { max-width:820px; margin:0 auto; padding:3rem 2.5rem 8rem; }
.section h2 { font-size:clamp(1.5rem,3vw,2.2rem); font-weight:200; letter-spacing:-.04em; line-height:1.15; margin-bottom:1.25rem; }
.section p { color:var(--text-2); font-weight:300; line-height:1.75; margin-bottom:1rem; }

.ablation-grid {
  display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px,1fr));
  gap: 1px; background: var(--border); border-radius: var(--radius);
  overflow: hidden; margin: 2.5rem 0;
}
.ablation-card {
  background: var(--bg); padding: 2.5rem 2rem;
  display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: .6rem;
}
[data-theme="dark"] .ablation-card { background: var(--bg2); }
.ablation-num {
  font-size: 3rem; font-weight: 200; letter-spacing: -.06em;
  font-family: var(--font); line-height: 1;
}
.ablation-fail .ablation-num { color: var(--sink); }
.ablation-win .ablation-num { color: var(--retrieval); }
.ablation-label { font-size: .82rem; font-weight: 500; color: var(--text); }
.ablation-card p { font-size: .82rem; color: var(--text-3); font-weight: 300; margin: 0; line-height: 1.5; }

.illusion-row {
  display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 1px;
  background: var(--border); border-radius: var(--radius); overflow: hidden;
  margin: 2.5rem 0;
}
@media (max-width: 600px) { .illusion-row { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }
.illusion-col { background: var(--bg); padding: 2rem; }
[data-theme="dark"] .illusion-col { background: var(--bg2); }
.illusion-col.fail { }
.illusion-verdict { font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 400; margin-bottom: .6rem; }
.illusion-col.ok .illusion-verdict { color: #1a7f64; }
[data-theme="dark"] .illusion-col.ok .illusion-verdict { color: #34d399; }
.illusion-col.fail .illusion-verdict { color: var(--sink); }
.illusion-col p { font-size: .85rem; color: var(--text-3); font-weight: 300; line-height: 1.55; margin: 0; }
</style>
